    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:b0ea93d1-47c6-473c-b395-bc996798abb9",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 34-year-old woman who appears mildly uncomfortable but not acutely ill. She is of average build, well groomed, and comes to clinic reporting 2 days of burning with urination, urinary frequency, and a persistent urge to void small amounts. She occasionally shifts in her seat because of suprapubic discomfort and says the symptoms have made it difficult to concentrate at work. She denies flank pain and is not visibly toxic, but she does look tired from waking multiple times overnight to urinate.\n\nShe works full time as a marketing coordinator in a busy office and often spends long stretches at her desk, sometimes delaying bathroom breaks during deadlines. She is socially active, enjoys weekend yoga classes, hiking with friends, and caring for her small dog. She lives with her long-term partner and says they recently returned from a short beach trip, during which she spent extended time in a wet swimsuit and was less consistent with hydration.\n\nHer daily routine is generally healthy, though she drinks several cups of coffee per day and admits her fluid intake is often \"not great\" during work hours. She drinks alcohol socially, does not smoke, and denies recreational drug use. She is sexually active with one partner and notes that her urinary symptoms began a day after intercourse. She tries to maintain a balanced diet and has no major functional limitations.\n\nFamily relationships are close; she speaks with her mother often and helps her younger sister with childcare on weekends. Friends describe {patientName} as organized and dependable, and she is frustrated that this otherwise routine infection is interrupting her normal schedule. She seeks care now because the dysuria and urinary urgency are worsening, and she noticed her urine has become cloudy with a stronger odor."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:ffac1b69-0d41-4908-8cfc-fcdc0309a271",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has a past medical history notable for seasonal allergic rhinitis and occasional tension headaches. She has no history of diabetes, kidney stones, chronic kidney disease, neurogenic bladder, or known structural urinary tract abnormalities. She recalls one prior uncomplicated UTI about 3 years ago that resolved with oral antibiotics without hospitalization.\n\nShe has never been hospitalized for urinary problems and has no history of pyelonephritis. Gynecologic history is unremarkable; menses are regular, and she denies current pregnancy. She uses a combined oral contraceptive pill for birth control. She is sexually active with one long-term male partner and reports no history of sexually transmitted infections. She does not routinely use spermicides.\n\nLifestyle factors relevant to the current illness include inconsistent hydration during workdays, frequent caffeine intake, occasionally postponing urination when busy, and recent intercourse before symptom onset. She does not smoke, drinks alcohol socially in small amounts, and exercises several times per week. There is no recent urinary catheter use or urologic instrumentation."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
